text: Glad to meet you all - and really cool to see <@U016C909613> and the team putting together an amazing program! I'm with the venture investment team at Consensys and bidding goodbye to summer here in Berlin. Looking forward to interacting more!

Nice to meet you everyone, and thanks <@U016C909613> for the invite.
It's Alex here, from Italy, I'm a serial entrepreneur, and the director of <https://mracrypto.com|MRA Crypto>.
My main focus is on *Distributed Governance* and *Collaborative Economics*, and in the last 4 years I've been helping developers and innovators to design and implement novel mechanisms of governance and tokenomics to support their distributed tech innovation.

I'm happy to start this new partnership with Gitcoin, and support this amazing, disruptive community.
Feel free to get in touch for any feedback and support in these areas :thumbsup:

Cheers,
Alex

I'm Nazzareno (naszam) a Blockchain Full-stack Engineer, Certified Ethereum Developer at Consensys Academy. Currently, Community Dev at MakerDAO, working on <https://github.com/makerdao/community/issues/537|Non-transferable Badges for Maker Ecosystem> Activity with Kernel Fellow Scott Herren, taking care of the <https://github.com/naszam/maker-badges|Smart Contracts>, hacked recently at  HackMoney as well in team MetaBadges. Won the ETHTurin Hackathon with Kernel Fellow Bianca Trovo' for the project <https://github.com/naszam/ants-review|Ants-Review>, A Protocol for Open Anonymous Peer-Reviews on Ethereum, taking care of the Smart Contracts and Architecture/Design.  Really passionate about Smart Contracts, De-Fi, DAOs, Token Economics, and all the awesome emerging technologies in the Blockchain Ecosystem. Also interested in Complex Systems, I'm an alumnus at SantaFe Institute, researching on Scalability, Eth 2.0, ... Looking forward to further develop Ants-Review and connect with Kernel fellows!

I wrote my dissertation last year on IoT x blockchain, including (pretty simple) agent-based models of blockchain networks in Mesa - might be some intersection there. Can I take a look at some of the work that came out of the Santa Fe Institute?

Hi <@U016PEM9U5B>, nice to meet you! Thanks! I've also worked on the architecture for an idea for a startup involving IoTs, Big Data and Blockchain that is currently in garage mode due to homomorphic encryption still in development (Aztec Protocol), and built a template called online-marketplace as the final project for the ConsenSys Academy Bootcamp, to be used to further develop the idea, like an Airbnb for Data on Ethereum. Regarding SantaFe I've completed two certifications you can find on my Linkedin, the last of which on Algorithmic Information Dynamics: A Computational Approach to Causality and Living Systems From Networks to Cells hosted by Hector Zenil, a new type of discrete calculus based on computer programming to study causation by generating mechanistic models to help find first principles of physical phenomena building up the next generation of machine learning. I'm interested in research more on that and apply the concepts and tools to address Scalability.

Hey everyone, quite the variety of backgrounds, I'm Julian Traversa, founder of Nescience Software & Capital, currently living just outside of Washington, D.C.

Before 2017/18, my background primarily revolved around the use of data analytics to establish psychological constructs. I then spent some time with a short lived professional gaming career before making the leap from data analysis to fintech when founding Nescience as an outlet for the tools I had begun to develop for the community.

At Nescience I developed an open-source rebalancing & direct indexing tool, the only current solution that keeps your API keys client side.
In addition, we released a propriety order-splitting algorithm which significantly increases market-making efficiency.

At EthDenver this year, I began the development of DefiHedge, a decentralized platform/protocol for fixed-rate lending & interest-rate derivatives, built on top of Compound.
I feel that interest-rate derivates are a natural progression in DeFi, and believe that rate-swaps, as the worlds most liquid derivatives, could propel DeFi far beyond its current status.
At this point in time, I have completed the design & implementation of the protocol (hybrid orderbook allowing both off-chain order & contract-fillable liquidity), and have moved on to the development of an exchange interface.

If anyone is intrigued by the project and has experience with best-practices while building an exchange using React, please reach out!
Also, if anyone has worked with libp2p and would like to contribute, we plan to implement a libp2p based relayer system similar to the 0x project, and will definitely be needing some help!

Hi everyone,

Grateful for the opportunity to be here! My name is Evan, and it is nice to see all of your introductions! I am a software developer based out of Washington DC, USA currently working full time as a software engineer building security tooling at IOV Labs. Outside of my day job, I have recently spent a lot of time thinking about the intersection of the environment and technology.

I recently consumed Netflix's documentary series Dirty Money where an episode on the company Formosa focused on big corp environmental impact seriously pissed me off, and caused me to conduct research into environmental law and technologically progressive technology companies.

While conducting this research, I discovered an inspiring company based out of France called <https://planetwatch.io/|PlanetWatch>. Their Algorand based environmental sensor is only in beta (and they do not appear to be overly responsive to people looking to join the beta :disappointed: ), so I am curious about creating alternative products that strive towards leveraging web 3 technologies to improve the quality and robustness of environmental monitoring systems (think Citizen Science crossed with web 3).

I hope to contribute software development as well as my passion for technology and the environment to Kernel, whether that be through pursuing some already existing project or finding like minded individuals to craft more widely available solutions similar in mission to what PlanetWatch is pursuing.

Looking forward to working with everyone, and please do not hesitate to hit me up if any of this sounds interesting to you!
Evan - let’s chat very soon - lots of overlap here :rocket:
